iconic scenes of African American college students sitting in quiet defiance at “whites only” lunch counters lies a series of underappreciated legal dilemmas—about the meaning of the Constitution, the capacity of legal institutions to remedy different forms of injustice, and the relationship between legal reform and social change. The students’ actions initiated a national conversation over whether the Constitution’s equal protection clause extended to the activities of private businesses that served the general public. The courts, the traditional focal point for accounts of constitutional disputes, played an important but ultimately secondary role in this story. The great victory of the sit-in movement came not in the Supreme Court, but in Congress, with the passage of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, landmark legislation that recognized the right African American students had claimed for themselves four years earlier. The Sit-Ins invites a broader understanding of how Americans contest and construct the meaning of their Constitution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightsxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican AmericansxHistoryy1877-1964. 0aAfrican Americans-Civil rights-History-20th century. 0aAfrican Americans-Civil rights-Southern States-History-20th century. 0aAfrican Americans-History-1877-1964. 0aCivil rights demonstrationszSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights demonstrationszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCivil rights demonstrations-Southern States-History-20th century. 0aCivil rights demonstrations-United States-History-20th century. 0aSouthern States-Race relations. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aCivil Rights Act.  aCongress.  aConstitution.  aSupreme Court.  a